:: Cafeteria {"position":"550,1575","size":"100,100"}
After I got my lunch, I immediately sat with Alice. Cafeteria was chaotic as usual. I sat across Alice, just eating, no talking, just silence until her mouth opened and let out;
	"You're overthing" she said as she sipped her drink like it was a normal saying 
    "I'm not.."
    "You're doing the eyebrow thing, hun"
    I frowned. What does she know about that? "What?"
    "That stressed eyebrow thing you do a lot"
    "Whatever" I rolled my eyes but couldn't stop the small smile coming out
Then, someone from behind us said
	"Yo, aren't you the girl that won all those singing competitions a while back?"
My body froze as if I was a Weeping Angel being looked at. I turned around. A junior. He looked curious
	"uh, yeah" I answered
    "Oh, wel, you gonna join the festival one, right?"
Jesus. What do I say, what do I say??? Alice didn't speak. She just looked at me, I think she wants me to answer truthfully. A simple question. Can't be hard, I think.
	"I... am still thinking about it"
    The junior nodded "Aw, dude, you should join. You were amazing" 
Were. The junior left and after he was out of sight, Alice leaned forward. I swear, I can never read this girl's face. She tilted her head and asked;
	"What really happened back then? You never told me" Her tone was serious
    "I- uhm" I stared at my tray. "It was this.. really big event.. and.." My mouth weakened, my appetite was no longer. Alice could sense it
	"Just tell me some other time. Come on, eat" She pushed my tray towards me
I'm glad to have her

[[Page 10]]


:: Nah, I'm good {"position":"550,2000","size":"100,100"}
“Uh— I can’t today,” I said, a little too quickly.

Alice blinked. “Oh. You sure?”

“Yeah. I just… have stuff to do,” I muttered, adjusting the strap of my bag. It wasn’t a very convincing excuse, but it was the first thing that came to mind.

She looked at me for a second like she was trying to figure out if I was lying. Knowing Alice, she probably already knew the answer.

“Alright,” she said finally, though her voice sounded a little unsure. “Don’t overthink too much, okay?”

I gave a small nod and forced a smile before turning toward the school gate.

The walk home felt longer than usual.

Cars passed by. A dog barked somewhere down the street. Someone’s music blasted faintly from a nearby house. Normally those sounds would just blend into the background, but today every little thing felt louder.

My mind kept replaying the same thoughts from earlier.

*You’re not special anymore.*

I kicked a small pebble on the sidewalk and watched it roll ahead of me.

Maybe going to Alice’s house would’ve been easier. She probably would’ve talked about random things, forced me to watch some dumb show, or complained about homework until I forgot what I was thinking about.

But instead, I was alone with my thoughts again.

When I reached my house, I pushed the door open and stepped inside. It was quiet. No one seemed to be home yet.

I slipped off my shoes and walked upstairs to my room. The first thing I saw when I opened the door was the shelf.

The trophies.

They sat there exactly the same as always, lined up neatly, shining faintly under the afternoon light coming through the window. For a moment, I just stood there staring at them. Three years ago, I used to look at that shelf with pride. Now it just felt like a reminder. A reminder of someone I used to be. 

I dropped my bag next to my desk and sat on the edge of my bed. The room was silent except for the ticking of the wall clock. My eyes drifted back to the trophies again. Without really thinking about it, I stood up and walked closer to the shelf.

My fingers brushed lightly against one of them.

District Vocal Competition — 1st Place.

I stared at the engraved letters. Back then, holding this trophy felt like proof that I was good at something. Now it almost felt like evidence against me. Proof that I had already peaked. I let my hand fall back to my side and sat down on the floor, leaning against the bed.

The house stayed quiet. And for the first time that day, there was nothing to distract me. Just me.  And the uncomfortable feeling that maybe I shouldn’t have said no to Alice.

[[Page 11.2]]


:: Page 1 {"position":"300,175","size":"100,100"}
And now, for our final show of the week, we have Melisa!!

I’ve been waiting for this, it’s finally my turn, hands shaking out of excitement, I walked up the stage and sang my heart out. It was a feeling I have been waiting to feel all week. It felt amazing. The audience cheered as I finished my final verse. 

*3 Years later*

	I wake up to the sound of my alarm. The ring that wakes me back up to reality, every day. My unfortunately, constant reminder. I got up and dragged myself downstairs and got ready for school. I opened my wardrobe and instinctively picked my Tuesday uniform to wear. I passed the shelf full of trophies. The shelf that I own, with all the trophies I earned. I used to think it’s mine, my eyes watered, fist clenched. I thought to myself, “I haven’t even won a single trophy this year, nor the year before that, nor the year before that.”

[[Page 2]]


:: Page 10 {"position":"550,1800","size":"100,100"}
	I picked at the food on my tray. Rice. Chicken. Something green that the cafeteria insists on calling vegetables, probably monkey meat with green dye. My fork hovered over it as if I was trying to solve Moriarty's riddle instead of eating lunch.

	Alice had already gone back to eating like nothing happened. I don’t know how she does that. One second she asks a question that nearly makes my brain short-circuit, the next second she’s casually chewing like the conversation didn’t just, I don't know stab me in the chest.

	I stabbed a piece of chicken with my fork. //You were amazing.// The junior’s words echoed again. //Were//. Why does everyone keep saying that word like it’s nothing? Like it’s just a normal thing to say. You were amazing. Not a 'you are.' Not you’re still good. Just… were.

	I pushed some rice around my tray. What if they’re right? What if that was just a phase? Like those child prodigies you see on TV who play piano at five years old and then disappear when they grow up. Maybe I was just one of those, temporary talents.

	I frowned. Why am I thinking about this again? I literally said I’m “still thinking about it.” That was a safe answer. Neutral. Non-committal. No one can hold me to it. But now that I said it… It almost sounded like I might join. Which is ridiculous. Right? My stomach twisted again.

Alice suddenly looked up. “You’re doing it again.”
	“Doing what?”
	“The thinking spiral.”
	“The what?”
	“You stare at your food like it called you a racial slur.”

“I’m just eating.”
“You haven’t taken a bite in thirty seconds.”

	I blinked. Huh, was it really that long? I finally took a bite just to prove her wrong. Alice smirked like she’d just won an argument without even trying. I hate how observant she is.

“So,” she said casually, “you’re thinking about joining.”

I almost choked.

“I didn’t say that.”
“You literally did.”
“I said I’m thinking about it.”
“Exactly.”
“That doesn’t mean I’m joining.”
“That doesn’t mean you’re not.”

I opened my mouth to argue, then stopped. Because technically… she was right. Dang it I hate when she’s right.

“I just don’t see the point,” I muttered.
“Since when do you need a point to sing?”
Since the day everything fell apart. But I didn’t say that. I shrugged instead. 
“It’s just a school festival.”

Alice leaned back in her chair.

“Yeah,” she said. “Exactly.”
I frowned. “What’s that supposed to mean?”
“It means it’s just a school festival, Lis.”

She gestured around the cafeteria.

  “No judges that decide your future. No huge crowd. No district finals. Just students trying stuff.”

She took another sip of her drink.

“You’re acting like it’s the Olympics.”

	I stared at my tray again. Maybe she’s right. But my brain doesn’t care about logic. Because every time I imagine standing on a stage again, My chest tightens. My throat dries. And all I can think about is silence. Five seconds of silence. Five seconds that still feel like the loudest moment of my life. I pushed the thought away and forced another bite of food. Alice didn’t say anything else. She just watched me for a moment. Then she sighed.

“You know,” she said quietly, “for someone who says she hates singing now…”

I looked up.

	“…you think about it a lot.”

I opened my mouth to deny it. But nothing came out. Because she was right. Again. And honestly? That might be the most annoying part.

	"The festival starts in two days. Think about this."
    
***

