:: Sure {"position":"175,2000","size":"100,100"}
"Sure, let me go ask my mom for permission."
"Alright"
The next few seconds were filled with silence. I feel like Alice wants to say something. Then, my mom answered
	//Yeah, sure, go ahead//
"Okay, let's go"
"Sweet, let's go, walking shouldn't take us too long"
"I guess it'll be fun"
The walk towards Alice's home was mostly filled with chatter of homework, boys, teachers, Lunar and Eclipse almost getting expelled, all that nice stuff. When we got to Alice's house, her parents weren't home, according to her, it was perfect timing. 

	We went up into her room and dropped our bags. I asked what we’re going to do since there’s no homework for today. She just looked at me and smirked, "have fun" she said as she threw a pillow at me. "Oh, it's on!" I hit her back with the pillow and it quicky escalated into a chaotic pillow fight. The room filled with giggles and laughter. We then proceeded to have cereal, not for breakfast, while watching shows. It was a lot of fun. I was so happy. We eventually just sat on the floor, not because of anything, just because we wanted to.
    "Lis" Alice called, she leaned forward towards me "You're my best friend, and nothing will change that." I froze. What? Why so sudden? "I don't care if your grades dropped, or stop attending competitions. I'll always love you, platonically of course, for who you are." She leaned on me and gave me a hug. I didn't react, well, I really wanted to. But, I honestly didn't know how to respond. 
    "Al-Alice, why so-" she cut me off
    "And I mean it" My eyes, they felt wet, moist
    "I- Thank you" I hugged back, with rivers of tears flowing down my face
    
    I haven't told her what happened that day. I'll tell her, now. Well, after I stop crying. The crying felt like hours, but, I didn't mind. I felt free, for the first time, from my thoughts and twisting stomach. 
    "I- I haven't told you.. what happened, I- I can tell you no-" She cut me off, again
    "Sure, after you stop crying, hun" She said with a smirk. I giggled. 
    
***

[[Page 11]]
    



:: Think more. Maybe you'll get your answer {"position":"175,1425","size":"100,100"}
//If I genuinely disappear from the spotlight... What would happen then? //
I imagined the next festival announcement for the year ahead. Someone else wins the singing competition. The people will clap, cheer them on. Maybe someone goes
"Wow, she just like Melisa used to be."
It felt as if a knife had stabbed my thoughts. They year after that, another singer. Another winner. Eventually, people stop mentioning my name at all. The trophies at home gather dust. Future visitor might be impressed, but they won't know me. They'll only see the past version. A ghost of my former self. My fingers tightened around my pen.

	And what about school? What if my grades keep slipping? What if everyone who once thought I was the "smart one" slowly realizes I just peaked. Will they whisper about it?
	//What happened to her?//
    //She used to be so good though//
My throat dried up like it was a desert. What will happen after high school ends? Everyone moves on. People chase their talents. Some become engineers, some become lawyers, some go to conservatories. Then, what do I become? The girl who peaked at fourteen?

Maybe this is the real fear. Not the stage. Not the competition. But, the iedea that the best version of me has passed and everything from now on is just... less. My pen tapped against the desk slowly.
  Tap.
  Tap.
  Tap.
The worksheet was still blank except for my name at the top. I stared at it. Maybe this is what being average feels like. And maybe the worst part isn't failing. Maybe the worst part is slowly realizing that...

I'm not special anymore.

***

[[Page 10.2]]
